1 Initial Data Analysis

Data Source

The two datasets used to produce this report (Master and Crosses) were derived from the [Scandinavian Runic-text Database] (http://www.nordiska.uu.se/forskn/samnord.htm) provided by Dr Alix Thoerming. It is not expected that the datasets provided are the most current versions available.

Data Reliability and Limitations

Given that archaeological data are often compiled by multiple people with little to now contact, these datasets are restricted to the reliability of subjective judgement. In addition, they are limited by the numerous incomplete values. In an effort to obtain clean data for certain analyses, rows with missing values have been filtered out, reducing the number of runestones available for analysis. This is flagged when appropriate throughout the report.

Variable Classification

The original Master dataset contains 4168 observations, representing a single rune, across 10 variables all classified as factors. Additional wrangling produced a Swedish only Master dataset, which is subsequently used for analysis throughout this report.

The Swedish Master data set contains 3220 observations, and covers only those runes found in Sweden. Several additional factor variables were created - provinces, earliestAD, latestAD - are the primary focus of this report.

The Crosses dataset contains 2397 runic observations across 54 variables: The signum variable (factor) is the primary key, Cross.Y.N (binary integer) indicates the presence of at least one cross, X. (integer) counts total crosses, and the remaining 51 variables (all integer) count the number of each particular type of cross.

Stakeholders

Potential stakeholders include historians, archaeologists and educational institutions interested in conduction research on, or teaching about, the Viking Age.


#Reads in master and crosses datasets

masterData = read.csv(file = "Arch_master_spreadsheet.csv", header = TRUE)
crossesData = read.csv(file = "Arch_crosses_spreadsheet.csv", header = TRUE)

#The remaining code in this block wrangles master dataset to create new variables to be used in analysis

##Create vectors for generalised style groups for earliest and latest dates. 
##Note: KB by itself is classified as no date as it is not mentioned in the data dictionary.

###No Dates available, start and end
NoDateAvailable = c("", "?", "KB", "KB?")

###Start Dates
RAKStartDate = c("RAK", "RAK?", "RAK? [Gräslund muntligt]", "Fp (RAK)", "RAK??", "Fp - RAK?", "RAK - Pr1?", "RAK [Gräslund muntligt]")
FPStartDate = c("? (Fp)", "Fp?", "FP", "Fp, Pr1?", "Pr1 - Pr2?; Fp [Källström 2007a:361]", "Fp??", "Fp, Pr1 - Pr2", "Fp", "Fp, Pr2 - Pr3", "Fp, Pr2", "Fp [Gräslund muntligt]", "Fp, Pr1") 
Pr1StartDate = c("Pr1", "Pr1? [Källström 2007a:362]", "Pr1 [En av, Ljung muntligt]", "Pr1 - Pr2", "Pr1 - Pr2? [Gräslund muntligt]", "Pr1 - Pr2?", "Pr1?", "Pr1 [Ljung muntligt]", "Pr1??")
Pr2StartDate = c("Pr2?", "sid a: Pr2, sid b: Pr2 - Pr3", "Pr2 [NOR 2004:27]", "Pr2 - Pr3?", "Pr2","Pr2 - Pr3", "KB? (Pr2 - Pr3)", "Pr2? [Klassificerad av redaktionen]", "Pr2 [Gräslund muntligt]", "Pr2 - Pr3 [Gräslund muntligt]", "Pr2 - Pr3? [Gräslund muntligt]", "KB, Pr2")
Pr3StartDate = c("Pr3 - Pr4?", "Pr3?", "Pr3 [Gräslund muntligt]", "Pr3 - Pr4 [Gräslund muntligt]", "Pr3? [Gräslund muntligt]", "Pr3??", "Pr3(?)", "Pr3", "Pr3 - Pr4", "Pr3 - Pr4??", "Pr3 [Fv 2009]", "Pr3 - Pr4? [Gräslund muntligt]")
Pr4StartDate = c("Pr4?", "Pr4 - Pr5", "Pr4", "Pr4? [Gräslund muntligt]", "Pr4 [Gräslund muntligt]", "Pr4 - Pr5?", "Pr4??", "Pr4 [Källström 2007a:407]")
Pr5StartDate = c("Pr5", "Pr5?", "Pr5? [Källström i SRI 10 Dig. suppl.]", "Pr5(?) [Fv 2012]")

###End dates
RAKEndDate = c("RAK", "RAK?", "RAK? [Gräslund muntligt]", "RAK??", "RAK [Gräslund muntligt]")
FPEndDate = c("? (Fp)", "Fp?", "FP", "Fp, Pr1?", "Pr1 - Pr2?; Fp [Källström 2007a:361]", "Fp??", "Fp, Pr1 - Pr2", "Fp", "Fp, Pr2", "Fp [Gräslund muntligt]", "Fp, Pr1", "Fp (RAK)", "Fp - RAK?") 
Pr1EndDate = c("Pr1", "Pr1? [Källström 2007a:362]", "Pr1 [En av, Ljung muntligt]", "Pr1?", "Pr1 [Ljung muntligt]", "Pr1??", "RAK - Pr1?")
Pr2EndDate = c("Pr2?", "Pr2 [NOR 2004:27]", "Pr2", "Pr2? [Klassificerad av redaktionen]", "Pr2 [Gräslund muntligt]", "KB, Pr2", "Pr1 - Pr2", "Pr1 - Pr2? [Gräslund muntligt]", "Pr1 - Pr2?")
Pr3EndDate = c("Pr3?", "Pr3 [Gräslund muntligt]", "Pr3? [Gräslund muntligt]", "Pr3??", "Pr3(?)", "Pr3", "Pr3 [Fv 2009]", "Pr2 - Pr3", "Fp, Pr2 - Pr3", "KB? (Pr2 - Pr3)", "sid a: Pr2, sid b: Pr2 - Pr3", "Pr2 - Pr3?", "Pr2 - Pr3 [Gräslund muntligt]", "Pr2 - Pr3? [Gräslund muntligt]")
Pr4EndDate = c("Pr4?", "Pr4", "Pr4? [Gräslund muntligt]", "Pr4 [Gräslund muntligt]", "Pr4??", "Pr4 [Källström 2007a:407]", "Pr3 - Pr4? [Gräslund muntligt]", "Pr3 - Pr4?", "Pr3 - Pr4 [Gräslund muntligt]", "Pr3 - Pr4", "Pr3 - Pr4??")
Pr5EndDate = c("Pr4 - Pr5", "Pr4 - Pr5?", "Pr5", "Pr5?", "Pr5? [Källström i SRI 10 Dig. suppl.]", "Pr5(?) [Fv 2012]")

swedishProvinces = c("Bo", "D", "G", "Gs", "Hs", "J", "Lp", "M", "Nä", "Sm", "Sö", "U", "Vg", "Vr", "Vs", "Ög", "Öl")

##clean up the masterData dataset for analysis
masterDataClean = masterData %>% 
              # add province column 
              mutate(province = as.factor(str_trim(str_sub(masterData$Signum, 1, 2)))) %>%
              mutate(provinces = as.factor(case_when(province == "Bo" ~ "Bohuslän",
                                                    province == "D" ~ "Dalarna",
                                                    province == "G" ~ "Gotland",
                                                    province == "Gs" ~ "Gästrikland",
                                                    province == "Hs" ~ "Hälsingland",
                                                    province == "J" ~ "Jämtland",
                                                    province == "Lp" ~ "Lappland",
                                                    province == "M" ~ "Medelpad",
                                                    province == "Nä" ~ "Närke",
                                                    province == "Sm" ~ "Småland",
                                                    province == "Sö" ~ "Södermanland",
                                                    province == "U" ~ "Uppland",
                                                    province == "Vg" ~ "Västergötland",
                                                    province == "Vr" ~ "Värmland",
                                                    province == "Vs" ~ "Västmanland",
                                                    province == "Ög" ~ "Östergötland",
                                                    province == "Öl" ~ "Öland",
                                                    TRUE ~ as.character(province)
                                                    ))) %>%
              # rename columns to english names
              rename(place = Plats, parish = Socken, jurisdiction = Härad, municipality = Kommun, 
                     coordinates = Koordinater, styleGroup = Stilgruppering, carver = Ristare,
                     material = Materialtyp, url = Bildlänk) %>%
              #filter province column to only runes found in Sweden as stated in data dictionary
              filter(province %in% swedishProvinces) %>%
              #drop unused levels once filtered out
              droplevels() %>%
              #add is column to indicate if individual signum is is the crosses dataset
              mutate(inCrosses = (Signum %in% crossesData$Signum)) %>%
              # create new column identifying earliest approximate start date based on style group
              mutate(earliestAD = as.factor(case_when(styleGroup %in% RAKStartDate ~ "990",
                                                      styleGroup %in% FPStartDate ~ "1010",
                                                      styleGroup %in% Pr1StartDate ~ "1010",
                                                      styleGroup %in% Pr2StartDate ~ "1020",
                                                      styleGroup %in% Pr3StartDate ~ "1050",
                                                      styleGroup %in% Pr4StartDate ~ "1060",
                                                      styleGroup %in% Pr5StartDate ~ "1100",
                                                      styleGroup %in% NoDateAvailable ~ NA_character_,
                                                      TRUE ~ as.character(styleGroup)))) %>%
              # create new column identifying latest approximate end date based on style group
              mutate(latestAD = as.factor(case_when(styleGroup %in% RAKEndDate ~ "1010",
                                                    styleGroup %in% FPEndDate ~ "1050",
                                                    styleGroup %in% Pr1EndDate ~ "1040",
                                                    styleGroup %in% Pr2EndDate ~ "1050",
                                                    styleGroup %in% Pr3EndDate ~ "1070",
                                                    styleGroup %in% Pr4EndDate ~ "1100",
                                                    styleGroup %in% Pr5EndDate ~ "1130",
                                                    styleGroup %in% NoDateAvailable ~ NA_character_,
                                                    TRUE ~ as.character(styleGroup)))) %>%
              #adds logic vector indicating if rune has a date allocated
              mutate(hasDate = (earliestAD %in% c("990", "1010", "1020", "1050", "1060", "1100")))

masterDataCleanNoNA = masterDataClean %>% filter(earliestAD != "NA" & latestAD != "NA")

merged = merge(masterDataCleanNoNA, crossesData, by = "Signum")

TimeNumCrossData <- merged %>%
  select(latestAD, 19)%>%
  filter(latestAD != "?" & latestAD != "")


write.csv(TimeNumCrossData, "TimeNumCrossData.csv") ### this file gets passed to the python program

2 Research Question

Are there any noticeable trends in how runestones and typological cross features are distributed throughout time and place?

Location

Vikings were the elite traders and occasional raiders that made up the Viking Age of Scandinavian history. They were active from the 8th to 11th century AD and settled in many parts of North-Western Europe, sporadically leaving behind various large, professionally carved runestone remnants. To date 4168 Viking runestones have been discovered across Europe, of which 3220 were in Sweden. The majority (42%) of these Swedish runestones were found in the province of Uppland, while only a single runestone has been found in Lappland (Figure 1).

#counts the total number of runes in each province
runesInProvince = ggplot(masterDataClean, aes(x = reorder(provinces, desc(provinces)) , colour = masterDataClean$provinces, fill = masterDataClean$provinces))

Dates

The precise dating of runestones has proven to be highly difficult through conventional methods. As large stones carry insufficient amounts of organic material required for carbon dating, various statistical and stylistic classification systems have instead been developed (Lewis, 2005; Thoeming, 2016). This data uses the classificatory system developed by Lager in 2002, where each stone is allocated into 51 sub-classes of 7 main groups, attempting to date the runestones by the carving design. Just over half of the Swedish runestones have been dated using the stylistic method (Figure 2).

#Compares how many runes have dates by provinces
runesInEarliestDateByProv = ggplot(masterDataClean, aes(x = (earliestAD %in% c("990", "1010", "1020", "1050", "1060", "1100")), fill = masterDataClean$provinces))

  theme(axis.title.x = element_text(margin = margin(t = 10, r = 0, b = 20, l = 0), face = "bold"), axis.ticks = element_blank(), axis.text.x = element_text(face = "bold", size = 10)) +
  xlab(paste("")) + 
  ylab("No. Runestones") +
  labs(fill = "Province") +

Figure 2. Number of runestones that have been dated using Lager’s stylistic method compared to those that have not date.

However, it is clearly not evenly distributed across the provinces. When we look at the proportion of dated to not dated runes on a province-by-province scale we see that a that only 5 of the 17 provinces have more than half of their runes dated (Figure 3). Similar to Simpson’s Paradox, when viewed from this perspective one might assume that current dating methods are not particularly comprehensive. While this view may not necessarily be right, this figure does still raise concerns for the ability of the current method to suggest dates for runes found in less represented provinces.

Crosses

Runes were designed to pay tribute to the life of a highly regarded individual, and were strategically located to mark territories. They were marked with runic text, decoration featuring stylised ‘rune animals’ and in some cases Christian crosses.

Only a subset of runes in the Swedish Master dataset also feature in the Crosses dataset (Figure X).

Figure 6. Density distribution of all runes found with a typological cross feature by latest allocate end date.

Since crosses have been characterized as explicit markers of the Christian faith, runestones can be indicative of the introduction and spread of Christianity across Sweden (Zilmer, 2011). By analysing the differences in the number of crosses across the time periods, the influence of political and historical changes on the spread of Christianity can be deduced.

For example, the violent conflict between Blot-Sweyn, (supported Paganism) and Inge the Elder (supported Christianity) during 1070-1100 was a major factor in the rise and fall of Christianity across Sweden (“Inge the Elder”, 2019). The relative dip in the number of crosses on runestones during that period (Figure 6) could be explained by the ousting of Inge and the introduction of Blot-Sweyn as the new Swedish King. However, after several years Inge returned to Sweden, slaying the king. This monumental event was said to ‘complete’ the Christianisation of Sweden during the Viking Era as suggested through the spike in the number of Crosses in the 1100 AD time period.

Hence, it could be deduced that political changes drastically influenced the existence of Christianity across Sweden.

Furthermore, a similar form of analysis (researching socio-political changes) could be performed to explain the trends in the number of runestones with a particular feature over time. Further investigations might find it interesting to determine the reason for the steady increase in the A2, C2, E2, E8 features over time (Figure 7).

  rename(f = feature)%>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_col(aes(x=latestAD, y=f)) +
  ylab(feature) + 
  theme(axis.title.y = element_text(margin = margin(t = 0, r = 10, b = 0, l = 0), face = "bold"), axis.text.y = element_text(size = 10)) + 
  theme(axis.title.x = element_text(margin = margin(t = 10, r = 0, b = 30, l = 0), face = "bold"), axis.ticks = element_blank(), axis.text.x = element_text(face = "bold", size = 10)) + 
  xlab("Latest Allocated End Date") + 
  ylab(paste("% of Runes with", feature, "Cross", sep=" ")) +
      theme(legend.position = "none")
  print(g)

}

3 Summary

In summary, this report has shown that Viking runestones are not evenly distributed both by time or by place within Sweden. It has also found that certain typological cross features show distinct trends over time, and that overall they may be explained by socio-political and religious events.

These findings suggest future studies may focus on dating techniques for runestones found in less represented provinces, or considering trends over time with respect to singular typological cross features.
